## Problem 1: 

The `infmort` data set from the package `faraway` gives the infant mortality rate for a variety of countries. The information is relatively out of date, but will be fun to graph. 
Visualize the data using by creating scatter plots of mortality vs income while faceting using `region` and setting color by `oil` export status. Utilize a $\log_{10}$ transformation for both `mortality` and `income` axes. This can be done either by doing the transformation inside the `aes()` command or by utilizing the `scale_x_log10()` or `scale_y_log10()` layers. The critical difference is if the scales are on the original vs log transformed scale. Experiment with both and see which you prefer.
```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
ggplot(data=infmort, aes(x=mortality, y=income))+
  geom_point(aes(color=oil))+
  facet_grid(region~.)+
  labs(
    x="Mortality",
    y="Income",
    title="Infant Mortality vs Income (w/o log10 Transformation)"
  )
```

a.  The `rownames()` of the table gives the country names and you should create a new column that contains the country names. *`rownames`
```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
infmort<-infmort%>%
  mutate(country=rownames(.))
```

b. Create scatter plots with the `log10()` transformation inside the `aes()`command.
```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
ggplot(data=infmort, aes(x=log10(mortality), y=log10(income)))+
  geom_point(aes(color=oil))+
  facet_grid(region~.)+
  labs(
    x="Mortality - log10",
    y="Income - log 10",
    title="Infant Mortality vs Income (w/ log10 Transformation)"
  )
```

c. Create the scatter plots using the `scale_x_log10()` and `scale_y_log10()`.Set the major and minor breaks to be useful and aesthetically pleasing.Comment on which version you find easier to read.
```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
ggplot(data=infmort, aes(x=mortality, y=income))+
  geom_point(aes(color=oil))+
  facet_grid(region~.)+
  scale_x_log10(breaks=c(10,100),minor_breaks=c(50,500))+
  scale_y_log10(breaks=c(100,1000,10000),minor_breaks=c(500,5000))+
  labs(
    x="Mortality - log10",
    y="Income - log 10",
    title="Infant Mortality vs Income (w/ log10 Transformation)"
  )
```
I decided to make the major numbers 10 and 100 because those are $10^1$ and $10^2$, and the minor breaks as halfway numbers (50,500,etc.) to show the reader of this graph that the graph is not on a normal linear scale, but instead on a log10 scale. I found this to be the most aesthetically pleasing because the numbers on the axes do not overlap at all.

